Concept Design with E–R Model
1. Introduction

Conceptual design is the first step in database design, where we identify:

What data is needed
How different data items are related

For this, we use the Entity–Relationship (E–R) Model, which represents data in a simple graphical form.

2. What is E–R Model?

The Entity–Relationship (E–R) Model is a high-level data model used to design databases by representing:

Entities (objects)
Attributes (properties)
Relationships (connections)

It was proposed by Peter Chen in 1976.

3. Components of E–R Model
a) Entity

An entity is a real-world object that can be uniquely identified.

👉 Examples: Student, Teacher, Course

Types of Entities:

Strong Entity: Has its own primary key (Student)
Weak Entity: Depends on another entity (Dependent)
b) Attribute

Attributes are the properties of an entity.

👉 Example:
Student → RollNo, Name, Age

Types:

Simple: Cannot be divided (Age)
Composite: Can be divided (Name → First, Last)
Derived: Calculated (Age from DOB)
Multivalued: Multiple values (Phone numbers)
Key Attribute: Unique identifier (RollNo)
c) Relationship

A relationship shows how two or more entities are connected.

👉 Example:
Student enrolls in Course

d) Cardinality

Cardinality defines how many entities are related.

One-to-One (1:1) → One student has one ID card
One-to-Many (1:M) → One teacher teaches many students
Many-to-Many (M:N) → Many students enroll in many courses
e) Participation
Total Participation: Every entity must participate
Partial Participation: Some entities may not participate
4. Steps in Conceptual Design using E–R Model
Identify entities
Identify attributes
Choose primary keys
Identify relationships
Define cardinality
Draw E–R diagram
Convert into tables
5. Example (Student–Course System)
Entities:
Student
Course
Attributes:
Student → RollNo, Name, Dept
Course → CourseID, Title
Relationship:
Enrolls
Cardinality:
Many-to-Many (M:N)
E–R Diagram (Explanation)
Student (rectangle)
Course (rectangle)
Enrolls (diamond)
Attributes (ovals) connected to entities
6. Conversion to Relational Tables
Student(RollNo, Name, Dept)

Course(CourseID, Title)

Enroll(RollNo, CourseID)
RollNo → Primary Key in Student
CourseID → Primary Key in Course
Enroll table uses both as Foreign Keys
7. Advantages of E–R Model
Easy to understand
Represents real-world data clearly
Helps in database design
Reduces errors
8. Conclusion

The E–R model helps in designing a clear and structured database by showing entities, attributes, and relationships, which can later be converted into tables.
